WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.313 --> 00:00:06.762
OWEN: Welcome.

00:00:06.762 --> 00:00:09.177
I'd like to welcome to
Google Ralph Simpson.

00:00:09.177 --> 00:00:13.041
Ralph is a 30-plus year
veteran of technology industry,

00:00:13.041 --> 00:00:14.510
recently retired.

00:00:14.510 --> 00:00:17.474
He volunteers at
History San Jose

00:00:17.474 --> 00:00:20.342
and is an avid collector
of cipher machines,

00:00:20.342 --> 00:00:22.732
has probably a couple
dozen cipher machines

00:00:22.732 --> 00:00:23.688
in his collection.

00:00:23.688 --> 00:00:25.122
And he's agreed
to come here today

00:00:25.122 --> 00:00:26.622
to tell us about
his Enigma machine.

00:00:26.622 --> 00:00:30.314
And he's going to be demoing it
and also letting people come up

00:00:30.314 --> 00:00:31.924
and play it with
afterwards, I guess.

00:00:31.924 --> 00:00:32.757
RALPH SIMPSON: Sure.

00:00:32.757 --> 00:00:34.822
OWEN: And so welcome, Ralph.

00:00:34.822 --> 00:00:39.372
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:39.372 --> 00:00:41.080
RALPH SIMPSON: Thank
you very much, Owen.

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:43.980
It's a real pleasure and an
honor for me to be here today.

00:00:43.980 --> 00:00:47.170
I really appreciate the time
that you are providing here

00:00:47.170 --> 00:00:47.880
for me.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:52.940
To be able to speak at a Google
Tech Talk is quite an honor.

00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:55.180
And I really look forward to it.

00:00:55.180 --> 00:01:00.490
This little machine here is not
only of great interest to me,

00:01:00.490 --> 00:01:06.580
I think it also reflects
a huge historical value,

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:11.090
both in terms of what it
meant in World War II,

00:01:11.090 --> 00:01:13.770
as well as what it
led to afterwards,

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:17.240
because in breaking the
code during World War II,

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:20.660
basically the Allies had to
come up with modern computing.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:24.250
And you could argue that the
computer revolution, Silicon

00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:27.830
Valley, and even Google
here has its roots back

00:01:27.830 --> 00:01:31.150
to this little humble
typewriter in a wooden box.

00:01:31.150 --> 00:01:33.000
And so what I'd
like to do today is

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.850
go through that early history,
the technology of the machine,

00:01:40.850 --> 00:01:43.266
and, let's see--
the early history,

00:01:43.266 --> 00:01:44.390
the technology the machine.

00:01:44.390 --> 00:01:46.820
I'll do a demonstration
as Owen mentioned.

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:49.620
And then I want to talk about
the significance of this

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:53.180
to World War II and how the
Allies actually broke the code

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:56.500
and how that led to
modern computing.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:01:59.990
Now there's at the
end a calculation

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:02.330
of the key length
of the Enigma, which

00:02:02.330 --> 00:02:04.050
I will not have
time to go through.

00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:05.010
But it's there.

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:06.320
It doesn't take a lot of math.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:07.986
And it is enlightening,
so I'd encourage

00:02:07.986 --> 00:02:11.990
you to use that as an
exercise with a reader.

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:14.200
It's really quite interesting.

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:18.730
So if you take a look at what
drove the need for something

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:21.280
like an Enigma
machine, it actually

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:25.260
started in World War I because
of the proliferation of radios

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:27.180
for the first time in warfare.

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:29.320
And that was a huge advantage.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:32.580
But after the war,
the Germans were

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:35.350
horrified to find out
that all of their messages

00:02:35.350 --> 00:02:37.480
were being read.

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:39.150
And it wasn't just the Germans.

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:41.140
Every single message
was being read.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:42.830
And part of the
reason is that if you

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:47.550
look at the types of cipher
devices that were available,

00:02:47.550 --> 00:02:50.470
they were really made for
a different environment.

00:02:50.470 --> 00:02:55.160
They were made in order to send
a message, a written message,

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:59.730
by courier or in some
other fashion where

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:01.120
it wasn't on a radio.

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:03.680
As soon as you're talking about
having hundreds or thousands

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.770
of messages on a radio
with the same code,

00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:08.570
that can easily be broken.

00:03:08.570 --> 00:03:11.520
Letter frequency
analysis, you identify

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.240
which letters are the most
frequent in the first letter

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:16.900
of each message, the second
letter, the third letter.

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:19.080
And generally you
can break these codes

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:21.350
in minutes, not hours.

00:03:21.350 --> 00:03:23.890
And I brought a few examples.

00:03:23.890 --> 00:03:30.570
You see on the left here,
it's called a Vigenere wheel.

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:32.950
This one was used by
the Confederate Army.

00:03:32.950 --> 00:03:36.645
It was invented in
the 1400s, so this

00:03:36.645 --> 00:03:38.340
has been around a long time.

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:41.640
Here is a life-size
replica of that wheel.

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:45.940
There's only five in existence,
so I had to get a replica.

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:47.670
But it's a very simple device.

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:51.180
You can see there's the
alphabet in two wheels here.

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:54.490
You just use a code
word and spin this

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:59.540
and come up with a new
algorithm for each code word.

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:02.760
Unfortunately, this
is easily broken.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:06.600
And in fact, the North broke
the Confederate Vigenere wheel

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:07.210
regularly.

00:04:07.210 --> 00:04:12.290
I mean, it was-- the South only
used three different code words

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:14.540
all during the war,
so it was quite easy

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:16.589
for them to break it.

00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:20.070
And that's despite the fact that
"Scientific American" magazine

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:25.289
in 1917 said this
device was unbreakable.

00:04:25.289 --> 00:04:26.330
Shows you what they know.

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:30.530
Here's another example.

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:33.570
Now, this one came out
just after World War I.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:37.940
But it was used by the Army
up through World War II.

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:41.470
This was invented by
the US Army in 1922.

00:04:41.470 --> 00:04:44.160
And you can see each of these
are separate wheels that

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:46.630
have the alphabet in a
different configuration

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.010
around the outside.

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:49.960
And the way it's
used is you just

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:54.460
write your message in
25 lines across this.

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:57.480
And then you spin this wheel
around and pick any other line

00:04:57.480 --> 00:04:59.530
to send as your gibberish.

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:02.619
And then the receiver
would print out

00:05:02.619 --> 00:05:05.160
that gibberish and then would
have to search around the wheel

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:08.920
to see something that looks
like normal English or German

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:10.430
or whatever your language is.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:13.780
But it was also
found in 1922, just

00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:16.990
by coincidence in Thomas
Jefferson's papers,

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:19.820
that actually he invented this.

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:22.060
I'm talking about
our second president.

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:23.640
He invented this device.

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:26.650
And his had 36
wheels instead of 25.

00:05:26.650 --> 00:05:28.475
But he described it exactly.

00:05:28.475 --> 00:05:30.100
And they actually
have an example of it

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:33.430
at the NSA Museum in
Fort Meade, Maryland,

00:05:33.430 --> 00:05:35.807
where you can take a look at it.

00:05:35.807 --> 00:05:37.390
By the way, if you
have any questions,

00:05:37.390 --> 00:05:40.932
feel free to ask me
as I go through this.

00:05:40.932 --> 00:05:42.390
Another thing I
wanted to show you,

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:47.670
I talked about this Vigenere
wheel and it's from the 1400s.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:49.540
That doesn't mean
that it ended there.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:53.060
Here is a US version
of that Vigenere wheel

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:56.150
that was used in
the Vietnam War.

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:57.680
Vietnam.

00:05:57.680 --> 00:06:01.290
And what you do is you take
this little thing down.

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:06.140
You attach a little
cassette tape to it.

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:10.580
And then the cassette tape,
by spinning this around,

00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:13.920
will put a different
Morse code on the tape.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.510
You can take this off and
then connect it to a radio.

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:20.580
And it would send it in a
blast mode very quickly.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:22.450
But it's using the
Vigenere wheel.

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.060
Now you may ask,
why in the world

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:26.920
would we use this in Vietnam
when obviously there's

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:30.110
much better technologies,
this one can be broken?

00:06:30.110 --> 00:06:32.890
Well, in battlefield
conditions, this is very fast.

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:34.380
It's easy to do.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:38.160
And if you only need to confuse
the enemy for an hour or two,

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:39.836
this works.

00:06:39.836 --> 00:06:45.080
If it's more than
that, it's not good.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:48.240
Now I wanted to show you
one other, or a couple more.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.450
Another one is a simple book.

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:54.740
This is a code book from 1988.

00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:56.584
It's called "Commercial
Cryptograph."

00:06:56.584 --> 00:06:59.000
There were military versions
of these types of code books.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.160
But it has words
and phrases written

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:05.280
on one side, other words and
numbers written on the other.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:10.100
And so you all you have to do
is just make up your message,

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:14.470
look up the words, and send
other words or other numbers.

00:07:14.470 --> 00:07:17.200
And that's how you send a code.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:20.810
This has also been in
use since the 1400s.

00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:24.550
And this is
relatively effective.

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:28.560
The problem is, as soon as
it's broken by losing a book,

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:29.820
you're dead in the water.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.740
And to then send out books to
thousands of army locations

00:07:33.740 --> 00:07:34.740
is just untenable.

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:38.160
So it was typically used
more for diplomatic locations

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:42.820
and high commands
and things like that.

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:47.470
And the last one I'll show
you is another US Army one,

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:50.180
just to show you what was used
by the US Army in World War II

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:53.190
to compare it to
the Enigma machine.

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:58.450
The Enigma machine
is a 26-pound device.

00:07:58.450 --> 00:07:59.410
It's a typewriter.

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:01.670
You press on a key,
a light lights up.

00:08:01.670 --> 00:08:03.520
Somebody has to write it down.

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:06.190
That somebody is usually
a second operator,

00:08:06.190 --> 00:08:08.290
so that they can go fast.

00:08:08.290 --> 00:08:11.240
This device is a little
bit different than that.

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:12.725
You can see there
are six wheels.

00:08:12.725 --> 00:08:14.730
It uses a whole
different technology.

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.110
There is no battery,
no electricity.

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:23.110
And actually it performs an XOR
exclusive or operation in this.

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:25.880
And then it prints
out the results.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:28.660
And it can cipher and decipher
just with the switch of a key

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:30.550
here.

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:35.780
So it's very handy,
smaller, easier to carry.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:37.409
No batteries needed.

00:08:37.409 --> 00:08:40.400
But not as effective, and
not as cryptologically strong

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:41.640
as the Enigma machine.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:44.290
So this one was used, again,
as a battlefield cipher.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:48.780
It was typically broken by the
Germans in a couple of hours.

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:49.900
OK.

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:53.510
So let me go on.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:56.830
What I wanted to show you was
kind of the background of what

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:59.200
environment was in place
when the Enigma machine was

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:02.850
invented, and why there was
a need for something that

00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:04.360
was stronger, that
could work better

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:07.614
than what was in
existence at the time.

00:09:07.614 --> 00:09:09.280
And it turns out that
the Enigma machine

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:12.450
wasn't the only
rotor-based cipher machine.

00:09:12.450 --> 00:09:14.800
Now, what was unique
about the Enigma

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:16.560
machine and these other
rotor-based cipher

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:19.420
machines is the rotor itself.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:21.260
This is the Enigma rotor.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:26.250
And as you can see, it has
these little pin connectors.

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:28.480
There's 26 of them,
representing all the letters

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:29.760
of the alphabet.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:34.170
On the other side
is the connectors.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:36.350
And what it has
in the middle are

00:09:36.350 --> 00:09:39.860
wires that will connect one
letter to a different letter.

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.380
So an A may be connected
to a G in this rotor,

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:45.600
but the A may be connected
to a B in one of the others.

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:47.480
They're all wired differently.

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:50.550
And so this is the
key innovation,

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:52.930
which maybe doesn't
sound all that great.

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:55.790
But at the time this was huge,
because when you put three

00:09:55.790 --> 00:10:03.690
in a row, that means that the
letter is changed three times.

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:05.800
And actually in the Enigma,
there's a reflector.

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:07.009
So it goes through.

00:10:07.009 --> 00:10:08.550
And then it goes
through a reflector.

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:12.010
It's changed again and then
gets changed three more times.

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:16.360
So this was quite an effective
way to encipher messages.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:18.730
The other thing was that
it made it very easy.

00:10:18.730 --> 00:10:20.230
If you notice on
some of the others,

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:23.720
it's a very manual
process, error-prone, a lot

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:25.000
of fiddling around.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.730
Here, you just type
on a typewriter.

00:10:27.730 --> 00:10:31.010
Much less room for error.

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:32.210
So that was the innovation.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:35.579
Now, it turns out that the
Enigma wasn't the only one that

00:10:35.579 --> 00:10:37.120
was invented in this
same time frame.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:40.230
Like I said, World
War I showed the need.

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:42.072
And so this was invented
around the world.

00:10:42.072 --> 00:10:43.530
There are four
different countries,

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:46.610
four different inventors
all within a few years

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:49.140
came up with this
same rotor concept.

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:53.070
And the first inventor was
here in the US, Edward Hebern.

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:57.070
He was actually in jail for
stealing a horse in 1915.

00:10:57.070 --> 00:10:59.760
And he said he came up with
the idea while he was in jail.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:03.410
And when he got out, he came
up with a really nifty-looking

00:11:03.410 --> 00:11:04.800
device.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:07.110
He didn't make a lot
of those, although he

00:11:07.110 --> 00:11:10.380
did get a million dollars
worth of investment money.

00:11:10.380 --> 00:11:13.660
He built a huge manufacturing
plant in Oakland

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:17.227
that was going to
house 1,500 workers.

00:11:17.227 --> 00:11:19.060
And after making a
couple of dozen machines,

00:11:19.060 --> 00:11:21.010
he went bankrupt.

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:23.630
And then he got thrown in jail
again for stock manipulation,

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:27.300
so that one went by the wayside.

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:29.510
Then we have the Enigma machine.

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:31.100
Now, that Enigma
machine you can see

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:33.680
is different than the one
that's sitting before you.

00:11:33.680 --> 00:11:35.160
That was the first version.

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:37.590
It weighed 110 pounds.

00:11:37.590 --> 00:11:40.320
And not a lot of those sold.

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:43.430
It was very cumbersome to use.

00:11:43.430 --> 00:11:46.060
And then by the mid
'20s, he came up

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:50.040
with this version, which
is a 26-pound device.

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:55.280
And it got accepted by
the German military.

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:58.610
Hugo Koch in Holland
came up with a design.

00:11:58.610 --> 00:12:02.290
He actually developed some
prototypes in the lab.

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:06.350
But they didn't work very
well, so he never really

00:12:06.350 --> 00:12:08.430
was able to sell
these commercially.

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:12.540
And Arvid Damm is
an interesting guy.

00:12:12.540 --> 00:12:15.650
He came up with a
device and sold some.

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:22.120
And in fact, the guy that bought
him out was named Hagelin.

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:24.410
Hagelin formed a company
called Crypto AG.

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:28.900
And the first big sale he had
was this device right here.

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:32.600
He sold 140,000 of these
to the US government,

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:35.384
which allowed him
then after the War

00:12:35.384 --> 00:12:40.110
to sell these around the world,
or a follow-on version of that.

00:12:40.110 --> 00:12:42.910
And he ended up selling
to 130 countries,

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:44.920
their military, diplomats.

00:12:44.920 --> 00:12:46.900
It was used everywhere.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.190
What wasn't known
was that the NSA

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:54.470
had a sweetheart deal with
them and had a back door.

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:58.170
So this story of the NSA
goes way back, right?

00:12:58.170 --> 00:12:59.620
This is from the '50s.

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:03.440
And that back door
existed for about 40 years

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:07.860
before it was unearthed
by Iran in 1999.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:09.920
So there's a whole history here.

00:13:09.920 --> 00:13:13.020
I could do a whole nother
Tech Talk on Hagelin.

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:14.450
But I have to go on.

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:18.660
And as you can see on
the next slide, what

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:21.710
I want to talk about now
is the Enigma machine.

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:24.020
Now, the Enigma was
invented, as you can see,

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:29.960
by Arthur Scherbius. w And Hugo
Koch was the other inventor

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:31.580
that I said never
got off the ground.

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:35.980
His device was too intermittent
and didn't work well.

00:13:35.980 --> 00:13:39.670
But in 1927, Scherbius
did a strange thing.

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:43.225
He bought the rights
to Koch's patent.

00:13:43.225 --> 00:13:44.725
Now, the reason I
say that's strange

00:13:44.725 --> 00:13:47.390
is Scherbius had
the earlier patent.

00:13:47.390 --> 00:13:50.950
And it turns out they
were identical patents.

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:53.250
So why would he buy this right?

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:54.600
It was never really understood.

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:58.690
It was kind of a
mystery, until 2003.

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:03.420
So here again in the story
of ciphering, a lot of times

00:14:03.420 --> 00:14:06.630
we find things out after the
fact, sometimes decades or even

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:08.450
hundreds of years
after the fact.

00:14:08.450 --> 00:14:11.620
And here what we found out was
that the rotor-based cipher

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:14.230
machine was not invented
by these four gentleman

00:14:14.230 --> 00:14:15.740
that I showed you earlier.

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:17.130
We have to rewrite history.

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:19.910
It was actually invented by
two Dutch Naval officers.

00:14:19.910 --> 00:14:22.840
They built a machine in 1915.

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:24.470
And that machine worked.

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:26.690
They showed it to
the Dutch Navy.

00:14:26.690 --> 00:14:28.920
And this was at
World War I time.

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:31.090
They decided to squelch it.

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:33.480
And they would not
allow these two Naval

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:35.730
officers to patent that device.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:38.400
And it just so happens
that the patent attorney

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:40.520
that these Dutch
Naval officers hired

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:43.620
was the brother-in-law
of Hugo Koch.

00:14:43.620 --> 00:14:45.170
What a coincidence.

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:48.120
And it turns out also
that Hugo Koch and Arthur

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:50.500
Scherbius were collaborators.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:53.170
So they worked together
in stealing the patent

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:54.730
and coming up with the Enigma.

00:14:54.730 --> 00:14:59.670
And I think that Scherbius
felt a little bit

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:01.640
like he owed
something to Hugo Koch

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:04.660
and gave him a little bit of
money to buy out his patent.

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:07.430
So that's the story
behind Hugo Koch.

00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:09.097
So after all of this
and all the stories

00:15:09.097 --> 00:15:10.638
you're going to read
about Hugo Koch,

00:15:10.638 --> 00:15:12.440
it turns out it's
these two Dutch Naval

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:14.890
officers that invented
the Enigma machine.

00:15:14.890 --> 00:15:15.390
Yes?

00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:17.640
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
idea who the two Dutch Naval

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:18.380
officers are?

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:18.690
RALPH SIMPSON: Yeah.

00:15:18.690 --> 00:15:19.190
Yeah.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:21.820
The question is, who are the
two Dutch Naval officers?

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:23.150
I don't know a lot about them.

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:24.220
I do know their names.

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:25.095
It's Theo van Hengel.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:32.330
And the other one
is RPC Stengler.

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:34.007
Those are the two
Dutch Naval officers.

00:15:34.007 --> 00:15:35.840
There's not a lot of
information about them.

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:38.940
But they were the
ones that invented it.

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:42.890
They were tasked to invent it,
basically, by the Dutch Navy.

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:44.650
And when they did,
the Dutch Navy

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:48.070
didn't want it out
for some reason.

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:50.170
It's also interesting
that they happened

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:54.170
to release that
requirement that they not

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:56.560
publish this or
get a patent on it.

00:15:56.560 --> 00:16:00.060
But Hugo Koch came
out with his patent

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:02.320
just two weeks
before that release.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:03.460
And so it was too late.

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:09.480
So here is a picture of it.

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:11.350
And you can see it
in front of you here.

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:16.600
This is a typewriter
type device.

00:16:16.600 --> 00:16:24.000
The innovation is these rotors
that messes up the alphabet.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.110
And the other thing
that I should mention

00:16:27.110 --> 00:16:28.710
is that the way
this works is when

00:16:28.710 --> 00:16:33.610
you press a key-- and
this key does two things.

00:16:33.610 --> 00:16:37.260
It advances the rotors
mechanically, not electrically.

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:39.750
And it sets up an
electrical signal

00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:42.040
that goes through
first the plug board--

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:45.800
and I'll discuss each of these
pieces more in just a minute.

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:47.710
But it first goes
through the plug board.

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:50.350
Then it goes through
each of the three rotors.

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:53.440
It goes through a
reflector, reflecting back

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:55.890
through the three rotors,
back to the plug board.

00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:57.850
And then it lights up a light.

00:16:57.850 --> 00:17:02.750
So it does create quite
a different algorithm,

00:17:02.750 --> 00:17:06.210
because that rotor will advance
every time you push a key.

00:17:06.210 --> 00:17:09.589
And it advances odometer style,
with the right one advancing

00:17:09.589 --> 00:17:14.099
once each time you press, the
next one advancing every 26

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:16.329
times, and so forth.

00:17:16.329 --> 00:17:19.720
So that's the way
this thing works.

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:21.290
I'll go through
each of the pieces

00:17:21.290 --> 00:17:24.690
here, just so you have a good
sense for what this is all

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:26.440
about.

00:17:26.440 --> 00:17:29.360
I really like the way that
they put this together.

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:30.470
It's 26 pounds.

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:31.610
It's very heavy.

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:36.260
But this thing is definite
German engineering.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:38.640
It's heavy duty, very well made.

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:43.080
You can see the keys are
made of stainless steel.

00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:45.680
This is over a
70-year-old device.

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:46.880
I've done nothing to it.

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:48.520
And it works right
out of the box.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:50.160
And I haven't had
to do anything to it

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:52.430
other than put a little
bit of oil on it.

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:55.630
And it works to this day.

00:17:55.630 --> 00:18:01.930
And you can tell it's very
strongly made, because it does

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:04.030
have to advance some
pretty heavy rotors.

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:06.810
So in other words, you
can't touch-type on this.

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:09.580
You have to push down
one letter at a time.

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:12.471
And it takes a bit of effort.

00:18:12.471 --> 00:18:13.970
The other thing I
should mention is,

00:18:13.970 --> 00:18:17.430
you'll notice that
there's only 26 keys.

00:18:17.430 --> 00:18:21.210
There's no special characters,
no numbers, anything else,

00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:23.490
no space bar.

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.890
So they don't allow that
in the cipher message.

00:18:26.890 --> 00:18:28.650
You have to write
out the numbers.

00:18:28.650 --> 00:18:32.850
They did allow an X
for a sentence stop.

00:18:32.850 --> 00:18:35.570
And basically, they ran
all the words together,

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:37.070
because you don't
want to give hints

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:40.470
on where the spaces or the
spacing of words could be.

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:42.190
So that's the way that works.

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:49.410
If you go to the next
element here-- so

00:18:49.410 --> 00:18:53.040
I'm going to go through the way
that the electrical signal will

00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:53.540
go.

00:18:53.540 --> 00:18:55.450
So next is the plug board.

00:18:55.450 --> 00:18:56.950
Now, as you can
see, the plug board

00:18:56.950 --> 00:19:00.580
is in the same format
as the typewriter keys.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:04.600
And the bulbs will be
in the same format.

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:08.030
It's a QWERTZ format,
not a QWERTY format.

00:19:08.030 --> 00:19:11.560
And basically what this does
is you attach one letter

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:12.800
to another.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:15.290
So if you were to
press-- for instance,

00:19:15.290 --> 00:19:18.589
here you can see
that I've got a Q

00:19:18.589 --> 00:19:19.880
and it's attached to something.

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:22.840
Let's call it the O. So
if you press a Q here,

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:24.920
it's going to
transfer that to an O

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:26.660
before it goes to the rotors.

00:19:26.660 --> 00:19:27.210
OK?

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:28.190
That's all it does.

00:19:28.190 --> 00:19:31.760
And coming back, if
it comes back as an O,

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:35.540
it'll change it to a
Q. That's all it does.

00:19:35.540 --> 00:19:38.790
This was something that
Scherbius did not design.

00:19:38.790 --> 00:19:45.230
So Scherbius designed all of
this sans this plug board.

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:47.990
And it turns out that the plug
board added more cryptological

00:19:47.990 --> 00:19:51.510
strength than all the rest of
the machine combined, which

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:52.510
is very interesting.

00:19:52.510 --> 00:19:54.330
So the military added that.

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:56.860
And they only used
it for the military.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:19:59.739
They continued to sell a
commercial version of this

00:19:59.739 --> 00:20:02.030
to other countries that did
not include the plug board.

00:20:04.580 --> 00:20:05.080
OK.

00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:08.560
And here is a picture
of the rotors.

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:11.060
And I think I showed
you these already.

00:20:11.060 --> 00:20:12.600
One thing I don't
think I mentioned

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:15.660
was there's a little notch here.

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:19.050
This notch can be moved to
any of the 26 characters.

00:20:19.050 --> 00:20:21.760
And what that notch does is,
when it's in the machine,

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:24.910
it sets the point for when
the next rotor to the left

00:20:24.910 --> 00:20:26.120
will advance.

00:20:26.120 --> 00:20:26.924
Yes?

00:20:26.924 --> 00:20:29.344
AUDIENCE: I noticed that
not all the plug board

00:20:29.344 --> 00:20:30.970
connections had connections.

00:20:30.970 --> 00:20:33.220
What happens when you don't
have the letter connected?

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:34.053
RALPH SIMPSON: Yeah.

00:20:34.053 --> 00:20:36.151
When it's not connected,
it basically bypasses.

00:20:36.151 --> 00:20:36.650
Oh.

00:20:36.650 --> 00:20:38.880
The question is that
not all the plug board

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:40.960
connections had a cable in it.

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:43.850
And that was done on purpose.

00:20:43.850 --> 00:20:49.430
And so if a letter was not
plugged, let's say a B,

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:54.130
the B just went straight
through without any change.

00:20:54.130 --> 00:20:54.630
OK.

00:20:54.630 --> 00:20:57.590
And so this is the rotors.

00:20:57.590 --> 00:21:00.800
You can see a couple
of facts about these.

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:02.230
I have three of them here.

00:21:02.230 --> 00:21:06.950
But in a general Army
Enigma situation,

00:21:06.950 --> 00:21:09.270
they would have
five to select from.

00:21:09.270 --> 00:21:11.800
And each day they would
have to change them.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:16.340
And therefore, you can have five
in one position, any of five,

00:21:16.340 --> 00:21:20.150
four, three, 60 different
combinations of rotors in this.

00:21:20.150 --> 00:21:23.530
You can also set this
on any of 26 letters.

00:21:23.530 --> 00:21:24.660
And there's three of them.

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:26.590
So it's 26 cubed.

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:30.530
And the notch can be set
on any of 26 positions.

00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:32.980
But only the right
two rotors matter.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:34.870
The left rotor isn't
going to move anything.

00:21:34.870 --> 00:21:39.040
So that gives you a sense
for the key strength

00:21:39.040 --> 00:21:41.120
of just the rotors.

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:43.440
It's actually not a big number.

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:47.730
In the Naval version of the
Enigma, they had four rotors.

00:21:47.730 --> 00:21:49.700
So that gave them
a little bit more.

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:53.070
And they also could select
from eight, instead of five,

00:21:53.070 --> 00:21:56.460
so that also gave them
a greater strength.

00:21:59.950 --> 00:22:03.660
Next that I want to talk
about is the reflector itself.

00:22:03.660 --> 00:22:05.560
The reflector is this
item here that you

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:07.730
see with the big
red B on it, just

00:22:07.730 --> 00:22:09.530
to the left of the three rotors.

00:22:09.530 --> 00:22:11.350
And what that does is
it takes the signal

00:22:11.350 --> 00:22:15.860
from the leftmost rotor and it
swaps it for another letter.

00:22:15.860 --> 00:22:18.780
And so it works much
like the plug board,

00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:21.620
but with all the
letters plugged.

00:22:21.620 --> 00:22:25.560
So if for instance
you come in as an A

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:30.290
and it was enciphered to a G,
if you came in to this reflector

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:32.970
with a G, it would come
out enciphered as an A.

00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:35.210
And the reason for
that is this allows

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:39.170
you to encipher and decipher
with the same code settings.

00:22:39.170 --> 00:22:40.840
Very handy.

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:43.530
Ease of use was all-important
on a battlefield,

00:22:43.530 --> 00:22:45.590
so this made it very easy.

00:22:45.590 --> 00:22:50.660
Also, this became
a very big home

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:53.050
in the design of the
Enigma, because what

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:56.590
it meant was no letter
could encipher to itself.

00:22:56.590 --> 00:22:58.920
And so keep that in mind
as I go through this,

00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:02.140
because that was a big hole.

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:04.290
But I think the
Germans felt that this

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:06.670
was important to be able
to encipher and decipher

00:23:06.670 --> 00:23:10.510
without having to change
keys or change settings.

00:23:10.510 --> 00:23:13.530
And so they left it that way.

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:15.580
All right.

00:23:15.580 --> 00:23:18.940
So the last section I
wanted to show you on this

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:20.980
is the lamp board.

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:23.660
The lamp board actually
has a small little light

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:26.300
underneath each of the
letters, so when you press down

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:28.510
on a key, a light lights up.

00:23:28.510 --> 00:23:29.640
It seems very simple.

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:32.190
But it goes through this
tremendous calculation

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:34.280
of changing letters.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:37.680
And the other thing
I should mention

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:40.415
is that there is
a battery in this.

00:23:40.415 --> 00:23:43.940
It's a square, fairly large 4
1/2 volt battery that was used

00:23:43.940 --> 00:23:45.730
in World War II.

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:49.360
I've replaced it with
two AA batteries,

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:50.470
which is only 3 volts.

00:23:50.470 --> 00:23:52.880
But it seems to work fine.

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:56.420
And also you can attach
this to a 220 volt

00:23:56.420 --> 00:24:00.240
plug, which was a
European power supply.

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:03.110
And so it works-- with
just a flip of the switch

00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:04.610
you can attach it to that.

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:08.220
Or you can attach it to a
transformer they also had.

00:24:08.220 --> 00:24:10.950
So there was multiple
ways to do this.

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:13.660
Within the lid here, you see
a couple of other things.

00:24:13.660 --> 00:24:17.510
There are some spare plug
cables for the plug board.

00:24:17.510 --> 00:24:19.590
There are some
spare light bulbs,

00:24:19.590 --> 00:24:22.050
in case you have a
burned-out light.

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:25.290
Interestingly, I've had this
machine for about 12 years.

00:24:25.290 --> 00:24:28.130
And I've never had a
light burn out yet.

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:29.394
Yes?

00:24:29.394 --> 00:24:32.035
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:32.035 --> 00:24:33.280
RALPH SIMPSON: To test what?

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:34.550
AUDIENCE: To test
all the lights.

00:24:34.550 --> 00:24:35.341
RALPH SIMPSON: Yes.

00:24:35.341 --> 00:24:36.250
Yes.

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:37.420
That's a good question.

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:40.064
So the question is, is there
a way to the test lights,

00:24:40.064 --> 00:24:41.980
rather than just trying
it, because how do you

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:44.430
know if the light's out, right?

00:24:44.430 --> 00:24:47.040
Well, they thought of
that, believe it or not.

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:49.120
So if you look
inside here, there's

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:54.420
a little empty plug here
that's written in German.

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:57.250
But it's basically a test plug.

00:24:57.250 --> 00:24:58.602
You just put the light in there.

00:24:58.602 --> 00:24:59.810
And if it lights up it works.

00:24:59.810 --> 00:25:01.900
If it doesn't, it's dead
and you throw it away.

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:06.840
And so they thought
of those things too.

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:08.350
OK.

00:25:08.350 --> 00:25:16.270
Oh, and also I have in
here a little light filter.

00:25:16.270 --> 00:25:19.790
It's really just
a tinted plastic.

00:25:19.790 --> 00:25:23.035
And what this is used for is
when you're in direct sunlight,

00:25:23.035 --> 00:25:26.070
it's sometimes hard to
see the light light up.

00:25:26.070 --> 00:25:32.000
And so when you put this in
here and cover the lights,

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.290
it actually shows up
a little bit better.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:37.510
And you can read these.

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:40.770
Now, I'm going to leave this
in place, because when we film,

00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:43.080
it turns out you can see
the letters light up better

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:47.250
even on video this way.

00:25:47.250 --> 00:25:49.590
