00:27:19.686 --> 00:27:23.020
So it's quite a large number.

00:27:23.020 --> 00:27:26.010
Now, the Germans weren't able
to achieve that, actually,

00:27:26.010 --> 00:27:28.240
because it would've taken
rooms full of rotors

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:30.560
and other inconveniences.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:34.140
So the way they used it
with just five rotors,

00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:37.700
the way they used the plug board
and so forth, what they saw

00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:41.812
was 10 to the 23rd, which
before the days of computers

00:27:41.812 --> 00:27:43.520
is nothing to sneeze
at, let me tell you.

00:27:43.520 --> 00:27:48.490
10 to the 23rd is still
equivalent to a 7y-bit key,

00:27:48.490 --> 00:27:52.300
which if you compare that with
the original DES standard which

00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:58.120
was used up until this century,
it's much better than that.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:28:00.680
But let's compare it to
what they were expecting.

00:28:00.680 --> 00:28:02.120
There were no computers.

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:05.020
They were expecting
brute force, manual type

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:06.700
of breaking of the key.

00:28:06.700 --> 00:28:11.860
And to break a key that has 10
to the 23rd as its key length,

00:28:11.860 --> 00:28:16.180
it would take 100,000 operators
each checking a different key

00:28:16.180 --> 00:28:20.280
every second 24 by 7 for
twice the age of universe

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:22.380
to break this machine.

00:28:22.380 --> 00:28:25.090
So I think they felt
pretty safe that this

00:28:25.090 --> 00:28:29.100
was a safe machine for them.

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:32.410
And by all rights,
it should have been.

00:28:32.410 --> 00:28:35.530
But let's talk about
how the Germans actually

00:28:35.530 --> 00:28:38.270
used this Enigma.

00:28:38.270 --> 00:28:41.730
First of all, they
had a daily key.

00:28:41.730 --> 00:28:43.950
And the daily key, I think
I've already hinted at,

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.360
there were five rotors.

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:50.670
They had to select three and
put them in a specific order.

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:52.670
That was the first set of keys.

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:58.670
Then they had to change the
notch setting for two of them.

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:00.600
That is another key.

00:29:00.600 --> 00:29:03.820
They had to change the
plug board settings.

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:05.420
Then they had to
place the rotors

00:29:05.420 --> 00:29:07.840
in a particular configuration.

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:10.830
Once they set that, they're
able to send a message.

00:29:10.830 --> 00:29:13.610
But they didn't just
code in a message.

00:29:13.610 --> 00:29:16.380
And the reason is, if you
have hundreds or thousands

00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:20.200
of messages all going with the
same key, that could easily

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:21.090
be broken.

00:29:21.090 --> 00:29:24.220
Letter frequency analysis
again will tell you

00:29:24.220 --> 00:29:27.680
what's the most frequent
letter of the first of each

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:29.890
of these messages, the second
letter in each message,

00:29:29.890 --> 00:29:30.850
and so forth.

00:29:30.850 --> 00:29:32.420
It would be quickly broken.

00:29:32.420 --> 00:29:34.670
So what they had
them do was they

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:38.890
had them send a
new rotor setting.

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:42.460
And they were told
specifically to make it random.

00:29:42.460 --> 00:29:45.820
And unfortunately,
what would happen

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:48.759
with the German operators
is they got lazy.

00:29:48.759 --> 00:29:50.300
And they would just
use three letters

00:29:50.300 --> 00:29:53.680
in a row, or three
columns in a row,

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:56.020
or sometimes their
girlfriend's initials.

00:29:56.020 --> 00:30:00.490
In fact, one operator had
a girlfriend named Cil.

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:06.160
And the British called this
type of breaking of code cillies

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:08.180
because it was so frequent.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:10.410
I mean, he typically
used that every day.

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:14.382
And so we could count on
him to help break codes.

00:30:14.382 --> 00:30:16.090
Now, another thing
that they did was they

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:19.900
sent that three-letter
new code twice.

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:21.660
And the reason for
that was they're

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:24.010
sending this by
Morse code, by radio.

00:30:24.010 --> 00:30:26.360
And sometimes that
would get garbled.

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:27.860
And they would want
to send it twice

00:30:27.860 --> 00:30:31.521
to make sure that it
was received correctly.

00:30:31.521 --> 00:30:32.520
So that's what they did.

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.560
They would send that twice.

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:40.350
And it turns out that that
slight problem that they

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:42.250
created, or that
slight shortcoming

00:30:42.250 --> 00:30:45.020
was exploited by the Polish.

00:30:45.020 --> 00:30:47.820
And they were able
to break the code.

