did they send it encoded
with the previous day's code?

00:39:03.010 --> 00:39:03.760
RALPH SIMPSON: No.

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:04.260
No.

00:39:04.260 --> 00:39:06.500
The question is, when they
sent out the daily code,

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:09.040
did they send it encoded
with the previous code?

00:39:09.040 --> 00:39:10.530
That would be one way to do it.

00:39:10.530 --> 00:39:13.810
But what they did was they
sent out a book that had 30

00:39:13.810 --> 00:39:16.230
days' worth of
codes written in it.

00:39:16.230 --> 00:39:19.630
If you were in the
submarine service, though,

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:22.850
you got three months'
worth of these codes.

00:39:22.850 --> 00:39:24.900
And so there again,
keep that in mind,

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:27.630
because that was one of
the shortcomings of this.

00:39:27.630 --> 00:39:30.640
And by stealing the code
books, you sometimes

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:32.379
were able to decipher this.

00:39:32.379 --> 00:39:33.795
And I think if
they sent it daily,

00:39:33.795 --> 00:39:36.612
it might have been a
better way to do it.

00:39:36.612 --> 00:39:38.070
AUDIENCE: If you
sent it daily, you

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:41.849
would have been able to decipher
all the codes any time you

00:39:41.849 --> 00:39:42.640
had one day's code.

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:42.931
RALPH SIMPSON: Yes.

00:39:42.931 --> 00:39:43.460
That's true.

00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:43.960
That's true.

00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:46.920
If you ever got one day's code,
yeah, that's the other fallacy,

00:39:46.920 --> 00:39:47.420
yeah.

00:39:47.420 --> 00:39:52.400
But the books were sent out
widely to all of the Army units

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:53.390
that had these.

00:39:53.390 --> 00:39:55.670
And there were tens
of thousands of them.

00:39:55.670 --> 00:39:58.480
So that was also dangerous.

00:39:58.480 --> 00:40:03.590
And sometimes the Allies
did steal those code books.

00:40:03.590 --> 00:40:04.170
Yes.

00:40:04.170 --> 00:40:04.980
Can I go back?

00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:09.094
AUDIENCE: Was there a
protocol for stolen code

00:40:09.094 --> 00:40:10.788
books or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:18.590
RALPH SIMPSON: I don't know if
there was a protocol, because I

00:40:18.590 --> 00:40:21.570
think this was something
that they did everything

00:40:21.570 --> 00:40:23.110
they could to prevent.

00:40:23.110 --> 00:40:27.260
So for instance on a submarine,
if a submarine was lost at sea

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:32.690
or they were sinking, they
were told to blow it up.

00:40:32.690 --> 00:40:35.240
Cipher machines, if the
enemy were approaching

00:40:35.240 --> 00:40:36.930
and they were
going to lose, they

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:39.600
were ordered to destroy the
cipher machines, the code

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.000
books, everything.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:46.620
The code books for the
boats and the submarines

00:40:46.620 --> 00:40:49.970
were made of a water-dissolvable
type of material.

00:40:49.970 --> 00:40:52.700
So if it got in the
ocean, it would dissolve.

00:40:52.700 --> 00:40:56.010
So there were a lot of
precautions that were taken.

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:59.790
And in fact, I think that
led to some of the reasons

00:40:59.790 --> 00:41:03.860
why there are so few Enigma
machines in existence today.

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:07.870
A lot of those were
destroyed by the Nazis

00:41:07.870 --> 00:41:12.160
as the Allies advanced
on their positions.

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:13.300
OK.

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:15.350
So that's the demonstration.

00:41:20.027 --> 00:41:22.360
I now want to talk about some
of the shortcomings, which

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:24.250
I've already been hinting at.

00:41:24.250 --> 00:41:28.930
You see here a picture of
Panzer General Heinz Guderian.

00:41:28.930 --> 00:41:32.420
And in the bottom left,
you'll see an Enigma machine.

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:35.170
And it's interesting that
there's an Enigma operator

00:41:35.170 --> 00:41:36.030
there.

00:41:36.030 --> 00:41:38.230
And beside him is the
person that would typically

00:41:38.230 --> 00:41:42.630
be telling him the message to
decipher and writing it down.

00:41:42.630 --> 00:41:46.280
And then the third person is the
person that operates the radio

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:48.250
and sends the Morse
code back and forth.

00:41:48.250 --> 00:41:50.370
So this is quite an
elaborate operation.

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:54.280
There's three operators
there to send a message.

00:41:54.280 --> 00:41:58.270
And in fact, I
would say that one

00:41:58.270 --> 00:42:03.030
of the shortcomings of this
machine is that it's so strong.

00:42:03.030 --> 00:42:05.680
And so let me elaborate.

00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:08.840
The cryptologic strength
of this was so good

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:11.710
that the Germans never
believed that it was broken,

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:14.640
all throughout the war
and afterwards, even when

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:17.730
they were presented with
pretty strong evidence

00:42:17.730 --> 00:42:19.920
that it was broken
and they were told

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:23.990
it was broken by their
allies, the Japanese.

00:42:23.990 --> 00:42:24.950
They didn't believe it.

00:42:24.950 --> 00:42:27.770
They didn't believe
that it could be broken.

00:42:27.770 --> 00:42:30.100
So that was one of
the shortcomings.

00:42:30.100 --> 00:42:31.880
Another is this
reflector design.

00:42:31.880 --> 00:42:34.530
I mentioned that it
allows for ease of use

00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:37.420
by deciphering and
enciphering with the same key.

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:40.530
But what it also
did was it made sure

00:42:40.530 --> 00:42:43.930
that no letter got
encoded to itself.

00:42:43.930 --> 00:42:47.180
And one of the ways that the
Allies liked to break codes

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:49.570
is come up with a crib.

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:53.570
And a crib is what they think
could be included in a message.

00:42:53.570 --> 00:42:57.800
And the Germans being very
precise in their language

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.350
and especially in
the military, we

00:43:00.350 --> 00:43:03.390
could count on them to use
certain words over and over

00:43:03.390 --> 00:43:04.380
in messages.

00:43:04.380 --> 00:43:06.090
And one of them was
a weather report

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:09.440
that went out to the minute
every day in the morning.

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:14.270
And the front of it
said weather report.

00:43:14.270 --> 00:43:18.100
And by using those words,
you can pretty well tell.

00:43:18.100 --> 00:43:20.830
You can eliminate a
lot of rotor positions,

00:43:20.830 --> 00:43:24.809
because you can't have
one letter coming back

00:43:24.809 --> 00:43:25.600
to the same letter.

00:43:25.600 --> 00:43:27.640
So it wouldn't necessarily
tell you the code.

00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:29.950
But it would tell you
which ones to eliminate.

00:43:29.950 --> 00:43:35.830
So you don't have the 10 to the
23rd key settings to try out.

00:43:35.830 --> 00:43:40.280
The other is that the rotors
had a regular odometer

00:43:40.280 --> 00:43:42.060
motion to them.

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:45.660
Now, it turns out that the US,
besides these 140,000 machines

00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:47.276
which were used in
the battlefield,

00:43:47.276 --> 00:43:48.650
had another machine
that was more

00:43:48.650 --> 00:43:51.410
similar to this called a SIGABA.

00:43:51.410 --> 00:43:54.410
And the difference between
the SIGABA and this

00:43:54.410 --> 00:43:59.090
is that it had 10 rotors
to change the letters.

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:01.310
And it had five other
rotors to change

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:05.020
the motion of those 10 rotors.

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:06.820
And it was irregular.

00:44:06.820 --> 00:44:08.640
And so by having an
irregular motion,

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:11.830
you've just added immensely
to the cryptologic strength.

00:44:11.830 --> 00:44:17.220
And in fact, that machine was
never broken by the Germans.

00:44:17.220 --> 00:44:19.900
But anyways, the
odometer movement

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:22.290
is a problem because
what that means

00:44:22.290 --> 00:44:26.710
is you're only changing
one rotor for 26 times.

00:44:26.710 --> 00:44:30.900
And then when this one flips,
you go in another 26 times only

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:33.860
changing that same
fast-moving rotor.

00:44:33.860 --> 00:44:38.760
And so the third rotor
actually never moves

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:40.230
in the entire message.

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:42.750
And the reason is that the
Germans were told never

00:44:42.750 --> 00:44:45.700
to send a message more
than 250 characters.

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:49.830
When you do, you go all over
again and send a new setting.

00:44:49.830 --> 00:44:55.210
And 250 wouldn't allow
that third rotor to move.

00:44:55.210 --> 00:44:58.050
So that was one of the problems.

00:44:58.050 --> 00:45:01.750
And another is
the lax operations

00:45:01.750 --> 00:45:03.860
by some of the
operators, especially

00:45:03.860 --> 00:45:08.260
in the Army and the
Air Force, for instance

00:45:08.260 --> 00:45:12.230
using girlfriend's initials
and things like that.

00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:14.090
Sometimes they
even went so far as

00:45:14.090 --> 00:45:18.690
to send a message twice
with different keys,

00:45:18.690 --> 00:45:22.840
like they accidentally didn't
reset the keys from yesterday

00:45:22.840 --> 00:45:25.630
and then they sent the same
message with today's key.

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:29.650
That's a huge, huge
problem for anybody

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:31.532
that understands
cryptography that you

00:45:31.532 --> 00:45:35.480
can break into a code that way.

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:39.420
So let me ask you, see that
Enigma machine in the corner?

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:40.860
I've blown it up here.

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:42.550
Is there anything
unusual that you

00:45:42.550 --> 00:45:45.908
can tell about that
Enigma machine?

00:45:45.908 --> 00:45:47.450
Can anybody spot it?

00:45:47.450 --> 00:45:48.830
It's not real obvious.

00:45:48.830 --> 00:45:49.572
Yes?

00:45:49.572 --> 00:45:50.750
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:50.750 --> 00:45:51.875
RALPH SIMPSON: What's that?

00:45:51.875 --> 00:45:52.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:53.300
RALPH SIMPSON: Yes.

00:45:53.300 --> 00:45:53.960
Exactly.

00:45:53.960 --> 00:45:56.560
It's missing a plug board.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:58.111
So, if you look at
this machine, it's

00:45:58.111 --> 00:45:59.610
actually not missing
the plug board.

00:45:59.610 --> 00:46:02.750
They put some white paper
or cardboard or something

00:46:02.750 --> 00:46:04.490
over the plug board.

00:46:04.490 --> 00:46:08.790
Now this was a picture
taken at World War II.

00:46:08.790 --> 00:46:11.744
Why would they cover over
the plug board, you may ask.

00:46:11.744 --> 00:46:12.660
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:13.413
RALPH SIMPSON: What's that?

00:46:13.413 --> 00:46:14.240
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:14.410
RALPH SIMPSON: Yeah.

00:46:14.410 --> 00:46:15.982
Those changed every day.

00:46:15.982 --> 00:46:16.940
They changed every day.

00:46:16.940 --> 00:46:20.720
So it's not a matter of
giving away a secret,

00:46:20.720 --> 00:46:23.970
or not a secret
of the plug board.

00:46:23.970 --> 00:46:26.430
But I have another
picture of a plug board.

00:46:26.430 --> 00:46:29.351
And you can see that
also has that covered.

00:46:29.351 --> 00:46:31.850
I went back and looked at a lot
of different Enigma pictures

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:35.500
from World War II that
came from the Germans.

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:37.730
And they all are
either covered over

00:46:37.730 --> 00:46:41.250
or they show it at an angle that
you can't see the plug board.

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:44.860
And I think it's because
this was a military edition.

00:46:44.860 --> 00:46:47.340
They felt it was
a secret edition.

00:46:47.340 --> 00:46:48.840
And all the other
Enigma machines

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:50.570
went out without a plug board.

00:46:50.570 --> 00:46:52.970
In fact, they also sold
these Enigma machines

00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:58.431
to the Italians and the
Japanese sans the plug board.

00:46:58.431 --> 00:46:58.930
Yes?

00:46:58.930 --> 00:46:59.728
Question?

00:46:59.728 --> 00:47:03.072
AUDIENCE: You sure it
wasn't just a wrist strap?

00:47:03.072 --> 00:47:04.780
RALPH SIMPSON: The
question is, am I sure

00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:06.680
it's not a wrist strap.

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:09.260
Well, if you put this
up, it doesn't really

00:47:09.260 --> 00:47:12.800
provide much of a
wrist rest there,

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:15.330
because you've got the
wooden board here anyways.

00:47:15.330 --> 00:47:18.030
And on top of that,
you're not touch-typing.

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:20.590
You have to push down
pretty hard on these things.

00:47:20.590 --> 00:47:23.410
So I though that
was interesting,

00:47:23.410 --> 00:47:26.100
that they felt that this plug
board was important enough

00:47:26.100 --> 00:47:27.850
that they kept it
covered in the pictures.

00:47:27.850 --> 00:47:28.350
Yes?

00:47:28.350 --> 00:47:30.235
AUDIENCE: So a machine
without a plug board

00:47:30.235 --> 00:47:32.205
would not be able
to decode a message

00:47:32.205 --> 00:47:33.580
from a machine
with a plug board?

00:47:33.580 --> 00:47:34.630
RALPH SIMPSON: That's right.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:35.130
Exactly.

00:47:35.130 --> 00:47:38.370
So the question is, if it didn't
have a plug board you couldn't

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:41.790
decode a message from a
machine with a plug board.

00:47:41.790 --> 00:47:47.200
And that's true, because that
adds a whole different levels.

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:48.709
Unless you took
out all the plugs.

00:47:48.709 --> 00:47:49.875
Then it would be equivalent.

00:47:54.230 --> 00:47:54.730
OK.

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:57.050
So let's talk about
how the Allies actually

00:47:57.050 --> 00:47:59.320
broke the Enigma code.

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:00.980
It was broken by the Polish.

00:48:00.980 --> 00:48:04.820
And I'm sure all of you
have heard the story.

00:48:04.820 --> 00:48:08.920
This seemed to be a little
bit kept secret, not secret,

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:10.396
but people thought
that the British

00:48:10.396 --> 00:48:11.520
are the ones that broke it.

00:48:11.520 --> 00:48:13.290
But actually the Polish did.

00:48:13.290 --> 00:48:17.240
And what happened was, in
1932, being between Germany

00:48:17.240 --> 00:48:20.800
and Russia, they
were very nervous

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:23.830
about the military buildup
of these large countries

00:48:23.830 --> 00:48:25.180
on their borders.

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:29.361
And so they were carefully
looking at the messages

00:48:29.361 --> 00:48:30.610
that the Germans were sending.

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:33.412
And they noticed a
difference in 1932.

00:48:33.412 --> 00:48:35.620
And that difference was it
looked like these were not

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:38.570
being coded with the same cipher
machines that they were using,

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:41.220
or the cipher devices they
were using in the past.

00:48:41.220 --> 00:48:43.630
And it was some kind
of machine cipher.

00:48:43.630 --> 00:48:46.940
They eventually were able to
reverse-engineer an Enigma

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:48.350
machine.

00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:50.870
They figured that out
through the commercial Enigma

00:48:50.870 --> 00:48:53.720
and saw that they also had
some kind of other swap,

00:48:53.720 --> 00:48:54.890
like the plug board.

00:48:54.890 --> 00:48:57.670
And so they
reverse-engineered it.

00:48:57.670 --> 00:49:00.070
And also the Polish
did something else.

00:49:00.070 --> 00:49:02.260
For the first time
in a cipher bureau,

00:49:02.260 --> 00:49:04.370
they hired mathematicians.

00:49:04.370 --> 00:49:08.240
And Marian Rejewski was
the main mathematician

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:11.750
that they hired who ended
up breaking the code.

00:49:11.750 --> 00:49:14.600
And it turns out
that they actually

00:49:14.600 --> 00:49:18.320
could not break the
code even with this.

00:49:18.320 --> 00:49:20.090
First of all, they
only had three people

00:49:20.090 --> 00:49:21.561
working on this in Poland.

00:49:21.561 --> 00:49:22.060
OK.

00:49:22.060 --> 00:49:24.610
Three mathematicians.

00:49:24.610 --> 00:49:32.250
But in 1933, it turns out
that the French approached

00:49:32.250 --> 00:49:37.210
an official in the cipher
bureau by the name of Hans-Thilo

00:49:37.210 --> 00:49:39.190
Schmidt.

00:49:39.190 --> 00:49:40.970
He got that position
because he's

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:46.210
the brother of a
decorated Panzer general.

00:49:46.210 --> 00:49:50.830
But this particular
person was in debt.

00:49:50.830 --> 00:49:52.230
He needed money.

00:49:52.230 --> 00:49:55.320
He spent a lot of money
on wine, women, and song.

00:49:55.320 --> 00:49:58.740
And as they say,
he wasted the rest.

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:02.210
Since he was in need of
money, he went to the French

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:06.330
and offered the Enigma
codes, the keys,

00:50:06.330 --> 00:50:08.800
and some diagrams of the Enigma.

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:13.000
And so the French took
it, gave it to the Poles

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:16.520
and to the English.

00:50:16.520 --> 00:50:19.720
And the French and English
could not break the code even

00:50:19.720 --> 00:50:21.050
with those keys.

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:23.580
Now, they could break
the codes for those days,

00:50:23.580 --> 00:50:26.400
but it didn't help them
break it afterward.

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:28.620
The Poles took that
information, got

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:30.990
the information about the
double-coding of the day's

00:50:30.990 --> 00:50:34.214
keys, the three-letter setting.

00:50:34.214 --> 00:50:36.130
They were able to figure
out that if you typed

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:42.400
TES twice, the T and the T, if
the second rotor hasn't moved

00:50:42.400 --> 00:50:44.560
gives you a hint,
and the E and the E

00:50:44.560 --> 00:50:46.810
and the S and S. You don't
know what letters they are,

00:50:46.810 --> 00:50:48.550
but you know that
they're the same.

00:50:48.550 --> 00:50:50.320
And so that gives
you a hint, if you

00:50:50.320 --> 00:50:54.550
had the rotor wiring
and the reflector wiring

00:50:54.550 --> 00:50:56.050
to help figure this out.

00:50:56.050 --> 00:50:58.170
And they were able
to figure it out.

00:50:58.170 --> 00:51:00.350
It's maybe not quite as
simple as I described.

00:51:00.350 --> 00:51:02.650
It still took quite a while.

00:51:02.650 --> 00:51:08.770
But they were able to figure
that out in 1933, early '33.

00:51:08.770 --> 00:51:13.670
They had broken the code and
were reading it until 1939

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:15.130
when they got invaded.

00:51:15.130 --> 00:51:17.710
And the day they got
invaded, September 1, '39,

00:51:17.710 --> 00:51:19.990
is the first day
of World War II.

00:51:19.990 --> 00:51:22.280
So they were successful in this.

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:24.840
It turns out that
in July of '39,

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:28.090
they finally told their allies,
the French, who had given them

00:51:28.090 --> 00:51:30.390
the way to break
it, and the English.

00:51:30.390 --> 00:51:32.050
And both the French
and English were

00:51:32.050 --> 00:51:33.920
astonished that
they'd been breaking

00:51:33.920 --> 00:51:38.310
this code for 6 and 1/2 years
and they had not themselves

00:51:38.310 --> 00:51:40.520
made any progress.

00:51:40.520 --> 00:51:43.190
And in fact,
besides breaking it,

00:51:43.190 --> 00:51:45.590
the Poles made what
they called a bombe.

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:51.100
It was a device that strung
together six Enigma machines

00:51:51.100 --> 00:51:53.840
and allowed them to break
the code much faster.

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:55.590
They were able to break
the code typically

00:51:55.590 --> 00:51:57.744
in about 15 minutes every day.

00:51:57.744 --> 00:51:59.160
And then the rest
of the day, they

00:51:59.160 --> 00:52:02.390
would decode them in
real time, just as fast

00:52:02.390 --> 00:52:04.150
as the Germans
were decoding them.

00:52:04.150 --> 00:52:06.810
And so this was
quite a breakthrough.

00:52:06.810 --> 00:52:08.380
They passed this along.

00:52:08.380 --> 00:52:10.570
And unfortunately
for them, they passed

00:52:10.570 --> 00:52:14.840
along replica machines, all
the information they had.

00:52:14.840 --> 00:52:18.315
And then very quickly afterwards
the Germans invaded Poland.

00:52:18.315 --> 00:52:21.410
And it was all over for them.

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:25.940
And so the UK set
up a major operation

00:52:25.940 --> 00:52:27.550
to help break this code.

00:52:27.550 --> 00:52:29.390
Here's their park.

00:52:29.390 --> 00:52:33.020
They bought this home
in Bletchley Park,

00:52:33.020 --> 00:52:34.330
north of London.

00:52:34.330 --> 00:52:37.730
They had up to 11,000
people working on this.

00:52:37.730 --> 00:52:38.980
Remember, the Poles had three.

00:52:42.060 --> 00:52:46.390
But to their credit, they had a
much tougher problem to solve.

00:52:46.390 --> 00:52:48.260
When the Poles had to
solve this problem,

00:52:48.260 --> 00:52:50.400
there were only three rotors.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:54.310
And so the three rotors
were in different positions,

00:52:54.310 --> 00:52:55.700
of which there's only six.

00:52:55.700 --> 00:52:59.780
That's why their
six-machine bombe worked.

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:03.490
But now that there's
five rotors to pick from,

00:53:03.490 --> 00:53:05.560
now all of a sudden you need 60.

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:11.780
They didn't have the ability to
create a bombe with 60 rotors.

00:53:11.780 --> 00:53:14.400
And so they left
it to the English.

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:18.000
Now, the English also could
have done a 60 rotor bombe.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.670
But that would have been
quite an undertaking.

00:53:20.670 --> 00:53:23.980
They figured out they
could do a 36-Engima bombe

00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:26.850
and manually eliminate
some of the settings

00:53:26.850 --> 00:53:29.570
and still figure out
the code fast enough.

00:53:29.570 --> 00:53:30.570
So that's what they did.

00:53:30.570 --> 00:53:34.080
They made a 36-machine bombe.

00:53:34.080 --> 00:53:39.800
And they were able to break the
code, typically in a few hours,

00:53:39.800 --> 00:53:43.570
because what it would do is
it would allow the operator

00:53:43.570 --> 00:53:45.295
to know which
settings could work.

00:53:45.295 --> 00:53:46.670
Then they'd have
to manually test

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:52.390
that setting and then go
on and test the next one.

00:53:52.390 --> 00:53:55.640
Also interestingly,
throughout the war

00:53:55.640 --> 00:53:58.220
the British were very careful
with this information.

00:53:58.220 --> 00:54:01.760
So if they got information
that said, for instance,

00:54:01.760 --> 00:54:04.550
that a submarine was going to
surface at a certain location

00:54:04.550 --> 00:54:09.140
to be resupplied
by a mother ship,

00:54:09.140 --> 00:54:12.230
they wouldn't just go and bomb
that location, because then it

00:54:12.230 --> 00:54:14.609
would give away that they
had read this message.

00:54:14.609 --> 00:54:16.650
So what they would do is
they would fly a spotter

00:54:16.650 --> 00:54:20.070
plane over it, make
sure the German saw it.

00:54:20.070 --> 00:54:23.610
Then their boat that
happened to be nearby

00:54:23.610 --> 00:54:28.270
would come over and
bomb it and blow it up.

00:54:28.270 --> 00:54:31.400
This almost backfired
on them once.

00:54:31.400 --> 00:54:33.870
They knew that there were going
to be two submarines being

00:54:33.870 --> 00:54:36.830
resupplied in this remote
location in the Atlantic.

00:54:36.830 --> 00:54:38.970
So they sent out
this spotter plane.

00:54:38.970 --> 00:54:39.970
They bombed it.

00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:41.709
But in that same
exact message it

00:54:41.709 --> 00:54:44.250
said that there were going to
be these other submarines going

00:54:44.250 --> 00:54:47.170
through this strait
in northern Europe.

00:54:47.170 --> 00:54:50.030
And they had to decide which
ones they wanted to bomb.

00:54:50.030 --> 00:54:52.670
They decided to get the
ones in the mid-Atlantic.

00:54:52.670 --> 00:54:55.500
Well, it turns out that
legitimately the Allies

00:54:55.500 --> 00:54:59.530
found these submarines
going through this strait.

00:54:59.530 --> 00:55:01.560
And they knocked
one of them out.

00:55:01.560 --> 00:55:04.530
And so this caused a big
concern by the British military.

00:55:04.530 --> 00:55:07.260
And in fact, Hitler
called a meeting

00:55:07.260 --> 00:55:12.720
that included the Navy, the
Air Force, and the Army.

00:55:12.720 --> 00:55:15.670
And all of the heads
of these groups

00:55:15.670 --> 00:55:20.240
came in to discuss
the possibility

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:22.682
that the Allies had
broken the code.

00:55:22.682 --> 00:55:24.140
But they also
brought in the person

00:55:24.140 --> 00:55:25.848
that was in charge of
the Enigma machine,

00:55:25.848 --> 00:55:28.490
who told them why it was
absolutely impossible for them

00:55:28.490 --> 00:55:29.674
to have broken this code.

00:55:29.674 --> 00:55:31.340
And so they all went
on their merry way.

00:55:31.340 --> 00:55:32.962
And nothing was done.

00:55:32.962 --> 00:55:34.920
They could have easily
started changing things.

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:36.128
But they didn't even do that.

00:55:39.370 --> 00:55:45.270
So let me set what was going
on in the North Atlantic

00:55:45.270 --> 00:55:46.690
with the U-boats.

00:55:46.690 --> 00:55:49.780
Before the US entered
the war, the U-boats

00:55:49.780 --> 00:55:51.400
were having a field day.

00:55:51.400 --> 00:55:56.070
They were sinking
Allied boats in droves.

00:55:56.070 --> 00:55:58.850
In the few months before
the US entered the war,

00:55:58.850 --> 00:56:03.240
it was 60 boats per month,
at a tremendous loss

00:56:03.240 --> 00:56:05.480
of life and loss of
supplies that were really

00:56:05.480 --> 00:56:08.540
needed for the war
effort for the Allies.

00:56:08.540 --> 00:56:11.150
The U-boats, the way they
would do this is they

00:56:11.150 --> 00:56:12.900
would form wolf packs.

00:56:12.900 --> 00:56:14.510
There would be a
number of U-boats

00:56:14.510 --> 00:56:17.410
all roaming around the Atlantic.

00:56:17.410 --> 00:56:20.020
They would spot a convoy,
because they were all

00:56:20.020 --> 00:56:20.940
separated.

00:56:20.940 --> 00:56:22.932
But rather than attack
it with one U-boat,

00:56:22.932 --> 00:56:24.890
they would send a message
back to headquarters.

00:56:24.890 --> 00:56:29.610
Headquarters would then
say, form a wolf pack.

00:56:29.610 --> 00:56:31.180
Here's the location.

00:56:31.180 --> 00:56:33.950
Maybe up to a dozen
U-boats would go there.

00:56:33.950 --> 00:56:36.230
And they'd all pick
out a different boat.

00:56:36.230 --> 00:56:38.450
And they'd fire on
them simultaneously.

00:56:38.450 --> 00:56:42.970
And it was at a tremendous
loss of life for the Allies.

00:56:42.970 --> 00:56:45.970
And this went on
for many months.

00:56:45.970 --> 00:56:51.790
So it turns out that this was
a major strategy of Hitler's.

00:56:51.790 --> 00:56:55.830
He was expecting that the UK
would capitulate and surrender

00:56:55.830 --> 00:57:00.581
because of this, because of this
blockade and lack of supplies.

00:57:00.581 --> 00:57:02.830
And you can see the quote
here from Winston Churchill.

00:57:02.830 --> 00:57:05.790
He said the only thing that
ever really frightened me

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:08.270
during the war was
the U-boat peril.

00:57:08.270 --> 00:57:13.330
Now this is despite the V-2
peril, the peril of D-Day

00:57:13.330 --> 00:57:17.954
and the landing there, all the
problems they had in Africa.

00:57:17.954 --> 00:57:20.370
The U-boat peril was the only
thing that really frightened

00:57:20.370 --> 00:57:23.040
him, and I think
for good reason.

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:25.853
I mean, this could have
lost the war for him.

00:57:29.560 --> 00:57:31.750
So here's what changed that.

00:57:31.750 --> 00:57:33.779
U-110.

00:57:33.779 --> 00:57:36.070
You've probably heard about
the movie or seen the movie

00:57:36.070 --> 00:57:37.870
"U-571."

00:57:37.870 --> 00:57:42.340
That was an important
U-boat that was captured,

00:57:42.340 --> 00:57:43.510
code keys and all that.

00:57:43.510 --> 00:57:46.670
But this was the
first one, the U-110.

00:57:46.670 --> 00:57:48.640
And here you see the captain.

00:57:48.640 --> 00:57:51.370
He was actually a hero in this.

00:57:51.370 --> 00:57:54.030
The U-boat was purposely
captured in a way

00:57:54.030 --> 00:57:59.240
that they wanted to get the
code keys from the U-boat.

00:57:59.240 --> 00:58:03.600
And so when it was bombed and it
surfaced, rather than just let

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:05.701
everybody surrender,
if they did,

00:58:05.701 --> 00:58:07.200
they would have
scuttled the U-boat.

00:58:07.200 --> 00:58:09.182
They would have set
off charges within it

00:58:09.182 --> 00:58:10.140
and it would have sank.

00:58:10.140 --> 00:58:13.850
So they purposely started
shooting at the tower

00:58:13.850 --> 00:58:16.130
to get everybody out of the
boat quickly before they

00:58:16.130 --> 00:58:18.310
could set these depth charges.

00:58:18.310 --> 00:58:19.510
And they did.

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:21.660
And by getting
everybody out quickly,

00:58:21.660 --> 00:58:23.510
they then rounded
them up and put them

00:58:23.510 --> 00:58:28.580
on the Allies' boat,
this "HMS Bulldog."

00:58:28.580 --> 00:58:31.280
And the captain saw
what was happening.

00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:34.610
And he saw that the
charges were not set.

00:58:34.610 --> 00:58:37.290
So he jumped in the
water to swim back

00:58:37.290 --> 00:58:40.250
to set the charges
to sink his boat.

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:43.800
And the Allies saw
that and killed him.

00:58:43.800 --> 00:58:46.990
And so the Allies went on board,
got all the Enigma machines,

00:58:46.990 --> 00:58:48.460
all the code books.

00:58:48.460 --> 00:58:52.040
And this boat happened to have
been out for about one month.

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:54.840
As I said, they have three
months' worth of code settings.

00:58:54.840 --> 00:58:57.570
So the Allies now had the next
two months' of code settings

00:58:57.570 --> 00:59:00.230
that they could
break very easily.

00:59:00.230 --> 00:59:01.840
And that's exactly
what they did.

00:59:01.840 --> 00:59:05.899
This single act is what changed
the Battle of the Atlantic.

00:59:05.899 --> 00:59:08.190
And the reason was, not only
did they have the next two

00:59:08.190 --> 00:59:11.460
months', it gave them insights
into the kinds of messages

00:59:11.460 --> 00:59:14.570
the Germans were sending, the
kinds of cribs they could look

00:59:14.570 --> 00:59:18.380
for, and how they could then
break future Enigma codes from

00:59:18.380 --> 00:59:20.440
the Navy.

00:59:20.440 --> 00:59:29.910
So here's how this goes back
to the beginning of computing.

00:59:29.910 --> 00:59:36.526
And the father of computing
is considered Alan Turing.

00:59:36.526 --> 00:59:39.585
[SOUNDS FROM LOUDSPEAKER]

00:59:39.585 --> 00:59:40.460
RALPH SIMPSON: Hello?

00:59:47.162 --> 00:59:47.970
OK.

00:59:47.970 --> 00:59:48.470
OK.

00:59:48.470 --> 00:59:50.370
So here's Alan Turing.

00:59:50.370 --> 00:59:54.270
He was the person that
led the effort in the UK

00:59:54.270 --> 00:59:57.040
in breaking the code.

00:59:57.040 --> 01:00:00.240
He was a mathematician,
who came up

01:00:00.240 --> 01:00:05.500
with-- he was the brains
behind breaking the code.

01:00:05.500 --> 01:00:10.370
And he came up with the
English version of the bombe.

01:00:10.370 --> 01:00:13.140
By the way the bombe
was named after they

01:00:13.140 --> 01:00:17.470
think an ice cream treat that
the Polish code breakers were

01:00:17.470 --> 01:00:20.160
eating at the time they
came up with the idea.

01:00:20.160 --> 01:00:24.310
But others say it could
be the ticking of a bomb.

01:00:24.310 --> 01:00:26.040
So we're not really sure.

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:29.270
In the UK, they built
210 of these things.

01:00:29.270 --> 01:00:32.390
Now these, as you can see,
they're not insignificant.

01:00:32.390 --> 01:00:34.270
They're quite large.

01:00:34.270 --> 01:00:37.070
The one you're looking at here
is the US version of the bome.

01:00:37.070 --> 01:00:43.670
The English version had a
column of three Enigma rotors.

01:00:43.670 --> 01:00:47.450
And it simulated 36 machines.

01:00:47.450 --> 01:00:49.780
These rotors on
the English version

01:00:49.780 --> 01:00:55.580
would spin about twice a second,
so quite fast, but slow enough

01:00:55.580 --> 01:00:59.000
that when they got a possible
hit it could just stop.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:01.870
The operator would then write
down that setting for someone

01:01:01.870 --> 01:01:03.695
to manually test
out to see if that

01:01:03.695 --> 01:01:04.937
could be a possible setting.

01:01:04.937 --> 01:01:06.770
Meanwhile, they would
start back the machine

01:01:06.770 --> 01:01:08.560
and it would spin again.

01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:12.000
Now, all of that would not have
worked for the Naval Enigma.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.550
And the reason is
there's just not

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:16.990
enough hours in
the day to do this.

01:01:16.990 --> 01:01:21.440
The Naval Enigma, having four
rotors selected from eight,

01:01:21.440 --> 01:01:25.220
it's hugely more
difficult to break.

01:01:25.220 --> 01:01:28.470
They also had a
selection of reflectors

01:01:28.470 --> 01:01:30.310
that I didn't mention
that were pluggable,

01:01:30.310 --> 01:01:32.150
so they could change
the reflector.

01:01:32.150 --> 01:01:34.920
So it was immensely
more complex.

01:01:34.920 --> 01:01:39.410
And so what the US did was they
invented a new kind of bombe.

01:01:39.410 --> 01:01:43.140
Not only did it have four
rotors and it spun faster--

01:01:43.140 --> 01:01:47.400
it spun at a rate of 29
revolutions per second.

01:01:47.400 --> 01:01:49.970
So the problem with that is--
well, first of all, the problem

01:01:49.970 --> 01:01:53.574
is the brushes wore out quickly
and it was tough to manage.

01:01:53.574 --> 01:01:55.490
But the other problem
was you couldn't stop it

01:01:55.490 --> 01:01:58.510
and then read the setting.

01:01:58.510 --> 01:02:00.320
It was spinning
too fast to stop it

01:02:00.320 --> 01:02:04.280
on a dime like that when it's
going 29 times per second.

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:08.140
So what they did was they
came up with a new invention.

01:02:08.140 --> 01:02:12.930
And that invention is
memory, believe it or not.

01:02:12.930 --> 01:02:14.800
So the top of that
machine, that box

01:02:14.800 --> 01:02:17.310
that you see on top,
that long box, that

01:02:17.310 --> 01:02:19.160
is memory for four
bytes of information.

01:02:19.160 --> 01:02:22.220
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:26.830
And you can see this
machine at the NSA cipher

01:02:26.830 --> 01:02:30.100
museum in Maryland.

01:02:30.100 --> 01:02:33.060
That top box held radio tubes.

01:02:33.060 --> 01:02:37.060
Each radio tube represented
a bit of information.

01:02:37.060 --> 01:02:41.960
And it held the four bytes
that represented the code here

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:44.080
of the rotor code.

01:02:44.080 --> 01:02:46.570
And it would print it out.

01:02:46.570 --> 01:02:48.370
So this was a major advance.

01:02:48.370 --> 01:02:52.190
And I would almost say this
is-- it's memory, right?

01:02:52.190 --> 01:02:56.550
So it's the beginning
of modern computing.

01:02:56.550 --> 01:02:59.130
The British also came
up with another machine

01:02:59.130 --> 01:03:02.400
to break a different type
of cipher device, which

01:03:02.400 --> 01:03:07.210
was the cipher device
they used for telegraphs.

01:03:07.210 --> 01:03:09.000
And that was called Colossus.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:15.660
And that also was another step
forward in modern computing,

01:03:15.660 --> 01:03:18.170
because it was programmable.

01:03:18.170 --> 01:03:21.720
So this is the
beginning of computing.

01:03:21.720 --> 01:03:23.720
This is what we're
talking about here

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:27.690
as far as this homely
little wooden box that

01:03:27.690 --> 01:03:33.280
looks like a typewriter set the
stage for things like computing

01:03:33.280 --> 01:03:39.500
and Silicon Valley and
Google and all of that.

01:03:39.500 --> 01:03:41.710
So by the end of
the war, the US was

01:03:41.710 --> 01:03:45.422
able to break the Naval
Enigma code in 12 hours.

01:03:45.422 --> 01:03:47.100
That's quite a while.

01:03:47.100 --> 01:03:50.530
But from then on, they
were broken in real time.

01:03:50.530 --> 01:03:52.852
So that was quite an
advantage that they had.

01:03:52.852 --> 01:03:58.280
They were able to identify
where these submarines were.They

01:03:58.280 --> 01:04:00.770
were able to blast
them out of the water.

01:04:00.770 --> 01:04:03.060
And it turned the tide.

01:04:03.060 --> 01:04:07.010
This turned the tide of
the Battle of the Atlantic.

01:04:07.010 --> 01:04:10.730
It was unfortunate that by
finding out where they were,

01:04:10.730 --> 01:04:14.560
they had to select which
convoys they were going to save.

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:16.350
They could not save them all.

01:04:16.350 --> 01:04:18.750
That would just give
away the entire secret.

01:04:18.750 --> 01:04:21.790
And then they would be
out, that information.

01:04:21.790 --> 01:04:23.990
So they would have
to selectively pick

01:04:23.990 --> 01:04:28.360
which ones they wanted
to take care of.

01:04:28.360 --> 01:04:31.580
Another way that they were able
to break these code that they

01:04:31.580 --> 01:04:34.350
found out was that
the weather trawlers,

01:04:34.350 --> 01:04:37.950
these were almost
unarmed small boats

01:04:37.950 --> 01:04:39.743
that they could easily capture.

01:04:39.743 --> 01:04:42.034
And they would have three
months' worth of Enigma codes

01:04:42.034 --> 01:04:42.790
on them.

01:04:42.790 --> 01:04:44.860
And they would
purposely, of course,

01:04:44.860 --> 01:04:48.470
sink them immediately and make
sure that the Germans never

01:04:48.470 --> 01:04:50.220
suspected that they
were really after them

01:04:50.220 --> 01:04:52.910
to get the code books.

01:04:52.910 --> 01:04:55.270
So what happened by
the end of the war

01:04:55.270 --> 01:05:02.100
was that 82% of the sailors that
went into service-- including

01:05:02.100 --> 01:05:06.060
the Admiral's son, Admiral
Donitz who was in charge of all

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:10.440
these, his son was one
of them-- died at sea.

01:05:10.440 --> 01:05:15.585
And 725 of 1,155
U-boats were gone.

01:05:15.585 --> 01:05:17.210
And in fact, toward
the end of the war,

01:05:17.210 --> 01:05:18.710
even before the end
of the war, they

01:05:18.710 --> 01:05:20.880
quit going out into the
Atlantic altogether.

01:05:20.880 --> 01:05:23.390
It just was not
fruitful for them.

01:05:23.390 --> 01:05:26.164
They were losing more submarines
than they were sinking boats.

01:05:28.890 --> 01:05:30.660
One of the things
that you'll read

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:33.880
if you read up on the
Enigma, a lot of people

01:05:33.880 --> 01:05:36.940
will claim that
breaking the Enigma

01:05:36.940 --> 01:05:41.680
allowed the Allies to shorten
the war by about two years.

01:05:41.680 --> 01:05:42.750
That's a made-up number.

01:05:42.750 --> 01:05:45.922
I don't know if it's true.

01:05:45.922 --> 01:05:47.380
But two years would
definitely have

01:05:47.380 --> 01:05:50.160
saved millions and
millions of lives.

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:52.710
I think there is no
doubt that whether it's

01:05:52.710 --> 01:05:54.680
two years, three
years, one year,

01:05:54.680 --> 01:05:57.880
it made a change and a
huge difference in the war.

01:05:57.880 --> 01:06:00.460
But even I think
greater than that

01:06:00.460 --> 01:06:04.620
was breaking it
allowed the invention

01:06:04.620 --> 01:06:09.515
of the modern computing, which
has changed our lives forever.

01:06:09.515 --> 01:06:19.080
And I think that is the
legacy of this device.

01:06:19.080 --> 01:06:22.030
Now, after World War II,
it's also interesting

01:06:22.030 --> 01:06:23.470
that a couple things happened.

01:06:23.470 --> 01:06:27.190
One was nothing happened.

01:06:27.190 --> 01:06:30.710
So here we have
this huge success.

01:06:30.710 --> 01:06:32.890
There were 11,000 people
working on breaking

01:06:32.890 --> 01:06:34.660
this code in the UK.

01:06:34.660 --> 01:06:37.440
And there were several
thousand in the US.

01:06:37.440 --> 01:06:40.150
And nobody told this secret.

01:06:40.150 --> 01:06:43.760
I can't imagine this happening
today in a day of Snowden

01:06:43.760 --> 01:06:45.860
and releases and all
that kind of stuff.

01:06:45.860 --> 01:06:51.430
But this was kept secret
for 30 years, until 1974.

01:06:51.430 --> 01:06:54.070
So in the meantime, there were
some of these Enigma machines

01:06:54.070 --> 01:06:56.390
around, some of them
without the plug boards.

01:06:56.390 --> 01:07:01.010
And the US and the UK encouraged
our allies to use these things.

01:07:01.010 --> 01:07:04.980
And our allies and enemies
alike used them for 30 years.

01:07:04.980 --> 01:07:07.910
And unbeknownst to them,
they were being cracked.

01:07:07.910 --> 01:07:12.420
And this particular machine came
from Norway, one of our allies.

01:07:12.420 --> 01:07:15.600
They were invaded early
on in World War II.

01:07:15.600 --> 01:07:17.650
The Germans left
behind these machines,

01:07:17.650 --> 01:07:20.060
because when they left,
they didn't have time

01:07:20.060 --> 01:07:23.730
to destroy all the things
they left behind in Norway.

01:07:23.730 --> 01:07:26.820
So Norway's secret police,
their equivalent of the CIA,

01:07:26.820 --> 01:07:29.430
used these machines
for 30 years,

01:07:29.430 --> 01:07:32.590
with the US and Britain decoding
every one of those messages.

01:07:32.590 --> 01:07:35.080
So in 1974, when
this was disclosed,

01:07:35.080 --> 01:07:37.080
they made these things surplus.

01:07:37.080 --> 01:07:39.430
And as a result, it went
on the surplus market

01:07:39.430 --> 01:07:41.010
and eventually into my hands.

01:07:43.670 --> 01:07:46.820
The other thing I should
mention is kind of a rarity.

01:07:46.820 --> 01:07:49.930
Some people ask me, how
many of these were made?

01:07:49.930 --> 01:07:51.240
How much are they worth?

01:07:51.240 --> 01:07:52.270
Those kind of things.

01:07:52.270 --> 01:07:55.690
We think about 30,000 of these
machines with the plug boards

01:07:55.690 --> 01:07:57.500
were made.

01:07:57.500 --> 01:08:02.320
We found serial numbers
up into 28,000's, so we're

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:05.400
assuming around
30,000 were made.

01:08:05.400 --> 01:08:09.720
Today, we know of
about 350 that exist.

01:08:09.720 --> 01:08:11.730
Half of those are in museums.

01:08:11.730 --> 01:08:14.260
Half are in private hands.

01:08:14.260 --> 01:08:16.600
And of those half that are
in private hands, about half

01:08:16.600 --> 01:08:17.700
of them are in the US.

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:20.389
So the US has half of them.

01:08:20.389 --> 01:08:24.649
The rest are scattered
around the rest of the world.

01:08:24.649 --> 01:08:27.670
And these things have
been quite collectible.

01:08:27.670 --> 01:08:30.390
Around the year 2000, you
could pick these things up

01:08:30.390 --> 01:08:32.560
for $20,000 or less.

01:08:32.560 --> 01:08:36.750
And they stayed that way
for quite a few years.

01:08:36.750 --> 01:08:40.220
I picked this up in 2002
for less than $20,000.

01:08:40.220 --> 01:08:45.770
But today, they seem to be
going for over $200,000.

01:08:45.770 --> 01:08:49.760
The highest that I know of
one selling for was $260,000.

01:08:49.760 --> 01:08:52.640
But oftentimes they're going
on Sotheby's or Christie's

01:08:52.640 --> 01:08:57.000
or something like that and
they're bringing $200,000,

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:01.542
I think partially because of
the added notoriety because

01:09:01.542 --> 01:09:03.250
of a couple of movies
that have come out.

01:09:03.250 --> 01:09:04.249
One was called "Enigma."

01:09:04.249 --> 01:09:08.260
One was called "U-571," which
depicts a US crew boarding

01:09:08.260 --> 01:09:10.743
a submarine and
stealing the codes.

01:09:10.743 --> 01:09:12.534
It's actually a British
crew that did this,

01:09:12.534 --> 01:09:18.279
so the British aren't
too happy with our movie.

01:09:18.279 --> 01:09:20.319
But that's what's happened.

01:09:20.319 --> 01:09:23.050
And I call this a collector's
item for the uber-geek.

01:09:23.050 --> 01:09:25.140
So I consider
myself an uber-geek

01:09:25.140 --> 01:09:26.370
for having such a thing.

