01:09:58.186 --> 01:10:02.146
AUDIENCE: What's the actual
origin of the word Enigma?

01:10:02.146 --> 01:10:04.770
RALPH SIMPSON: I don't know the
actual-- some people have asked

01:10:04.770 --> 01:10:09.650
me, because they think did the
US or the British use this word

01:10:09.650 --> 01:10:12.050
and the Germans did not.

01:10:12.050 --> 01:10:14.990
It turns out enigma means
the same thing in German

01:10:14.990 --> 01:10:15.980
as it does in English.

01:10:15.980 --> 01:10:17.470
And it's spelled the same way.

01:10:17.470 --> 01:10:19.386
Now, I don't know if
that's part of the reason

01:10:19.386 --> 01:10:21.840
that Scherbius picked that name.

01:10:21.840 --> 01:10:24.900
But enigma means the same thing.

01:10:24.900 --> 01:10:28.690
It's a puzzle, a tough puzzle
to break or something like that.

01:10:28.690 --> 01:10:31.070
And it's identical
in both languages

01:10:31.070 --> 01:10:32.140
and spelled the same way.

01:10:32.140 --> 01:10:34.259
So maybe that's just fortunate.

01:10:34.259 --> 01:10:34.800
I don't know.

01:10:34.800 --> 01:10:39.970
But I'm not sure of the
original origin of the name.

01:10:39.970 --> 01:10:40.470
Yes?

